            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "I assume this overlaps with the \"multihead\" story,\n\n- https://github.com/neovim/neovim/issues/2161\n\nand for \"multihead\", I've always assumed that the most feasible, simple, and easy-to-reason-about approach is for each client to \"own\" a subset of tabpages. Then you get client-specific layouts \"for free\", because each client is just showing a different subset of tabpages.\n\nThe Nvim server itself has the full set of tabpages; but each client only shows its subset. Clients could be allowed to somehow show non-owned tabpages, but the owner's rules will apply.\n\nThen the design is oriented around enhancing tabpages. Each tabpage has its own:\n\n- \"screen size\"\n- colorscheme\n- ...?\n\nThis would be somewhat straightforward if the Nvim server switchs the \"current\" tabpage whenever a client is focused. But that means if 2 clients are showing side-by-side, they will show the same thing. A compromise would be for the non-current client to show a \"stale\" view (i.e. the server state switches, but the unfocused client shows a client-side snapshot); it would not show any animations or anything until it is focused again.",
